canized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames, such as   Frankel  .","History: The American statesman and scientist Benjamin Franklin (1706–90) was the son of Josiah Franklin, a chandler (dealer in soap and candles), who had emigrated <i>c.</i> 1682 from Ecton, Northamptonshire, to Boston, MA, where his son was born."],"variants":[{"name":"Franklyn","meanings":["English: variant of   Franklin  ."]},{"name":"Frankland","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Franklin  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>, a status name from Middle English <i>frankeleyn</i> ‘freeman, freeholder, land-owner of free but not noble birth’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>fraunclein</i>) for someone who lived on a piece of land held without obligations of rent or service. Compare   Freeland  ."]},{"name":"Frankel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Moshe, Benzion, Hyman, Leibish, Mayer, Meyer, Nachum, Yitzchok, Ari, Chaim, Dov.","German (mainly <b>Fränkel</b>) and Jewish (Ashkenazic; also <b>Fränkel</b>): variant of   Frankl  . Compare   Fraenkel  .","History: This is one of the old Ashkenazic surnames. In Eastern Europe, it was used by rabbinical families well before the mass adoption of surnames by local Jews at the turn of the 19th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Franklin was born about 1520, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Franklin."},"et":{"abt 1520–":"umbes 1520–Surnud","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","1570":"1570","1549":"1549","abt 1520":"umbes 1520","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"abt 1520–":"noin 1520–Kuollut","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1520–Female":"1520–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","1570":"1570","1549":"1549","abt 1520":"noin 1520","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"abt 1520–":"environ 1520–Décédée","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1520–Female":"1520–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","1570":"1570","1549":"1549","abt 1520":"environ 1520","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Franklin est née environ 1520, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Sir Franklin."},"de":{"abt 1520–":"um 1520–Verstorben","1520–Male":"1520–Verstorben","1540–1570":"1540–1570","1520–Female":"1520–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","1570":"1570","1549":"1549","abt 1520":"um 1520","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Franklin wurde um 1520 in England g